[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and independently discovered by Donald Knuth "a few weeks later" from automata theory.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and Vaughan Pratt published a technical report in 1970.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The three also published the algorithm jointly in 1977.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Independently, in 1969, Matiyasevich discovered a similar algorithm, coded by a two-dimensional Turing machine, while studying a string-pattern-matching recognition problem over a binary alphabet.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This was the first linear-time algorithm for string matching.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A string-matching algorithm wants to find the starting index `m` in string `s` that matches the search word `w`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The most straightforward algorithm, known as the "brute-force" or "naive" algorithm, is to look for a word match at each index `m`, i.e. the position in the string being searched that corresponds to the character `s[m]`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At each position `m` the algorithm first checks for equality of the first character in the word being searched, i.e.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a match is found, the algorithm tests the other characters in the word being searched by checking successive values of the word position index, `i`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm retrieves the character `w[i]` in the word being searched and checks for equality of the expression `S[m+i] =?
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If all successive characters match in `W` at position `m`, then a match is found at that position in the search string.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the index `m` reaches the end of the string then there is no match, in which case the search is said to "fail".
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Usually, the trial check will quickly reject the trial match.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are uniformly distributed random letters, then the chance that characters match is 1 in 26.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In most cases, the trial check will reject the match at the initial letter.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The chance that the first two letters will match is 1 in 676 (1 in 26^2 chances of a match over 26 possible letters).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] So if the characters are random, then the expected complexity of searching string `s` of length *n* is on the order of *n* comparisons or *Θ*(*n*).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `s` is 1 million characters and `w` is 1000 characters, then the string search should complete after about 1.04 million character comparisons.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] That expected performance is not guaranteed.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are not random, then checking a trial `m` may take many character comparisons.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The worst case is if the two strings match in all but the last letter.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Imagine that the string `s` consists of 1 million characters that are all *A*, and that the word `w` is 999 *A* characters terminating in a final *B* character.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string-matching algorithm will now examine 1000 characters at each trial position before rejecting the match and advancing the trial position.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string search example would now take about 1000 character comparisons times 1 million positions for 1 billion character comparisons.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the length of `w` is *k*, then the worst-case performance is *O*(*k*⋅*n*).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The KMP algorithm has a better worst-case performance than the straightforward algorithm.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP spends a little time precomputing a table (on the order of the size of `w`, *O*(*k*)), and then it uses that table to do an efficient search of the string in *O*(*n*).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The difference is that KMP makes use of previous match information that the straightforward algorithm does not.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In the example above, when KMP sees a trial match fail on the 1000th character (`i` = 999) because `s[m + 999] ≠ w[999]`, it will increment `m` by 1, but it will know that the first 998 characters at the new position already match.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP matched 999 *A* characters before discovering a mismatch at the 1000th character (position 999).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Advancing the trial match position `m` by one throws away the first *A*, so KMP knows there are 998 *A* characters that match `w` and does not retest them; that is, KMP sets `i` to 998.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP maintains its knowledge in the precomputed table and two state variables.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] When KMP discovers a mismatch, the table determines how much KMP will increase (variable `m`) and where it will resume testing (variable `i`).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To illustrate the algorithm's details, consider a (relatively artificial) run of the algorithm, where `W` = "ABCDABD" and `S` = "ABC ABCDAB ABCDABCDABDE".
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In each step the algorithm compares `S[m+i]` with `W[i]` and increments `i` if they are equal.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm compares successive characters of `W` to "parallel" characters of `S`, moving from one to the next by incrementing `i` if they match.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, in the fourth step `S[3] = ' '` does not match `W[3] = 'D'`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Rather than beginning to search again at `S[1]`, we note that no `'A'` occurs between positions 1 and 2 in `S`; hence, having checked all those characters previously (and knowing they matched the corresponding characters in `W`), there is no chance of finding the beginning of a match.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm sets `m = 3` and `i = 0`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here, `i` increments through a nearly complete match `"ABCDAB"` until `i = 6` giving a mismatch at `W[6]` and `S[10]`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, just prior to the end of the current partial match, there was that substring `"AB"` that could be the beginning of a new match, so the algorithm must take this into consideration.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As these characters match the two characters prior to the current position, those characters need not be checked again; the algorithm sets `m = 8` (the start of the initial prefix) and `i = 2` (signaling the first two characters match) and continues matching.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the algorithm not only omits previously matched characters of `S` (the `"AB"`), but also previously matched characters of `W` (the prefix `"AB"`).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This search at the new position fails immediately because `W[2]` (a `'C'`) does not match `S[10]` (a `' '`).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As in the first trial, the mismatch causes the algorithm to return to the beginning of `W` and begins searching at the mismatched character position of `S`: `m = 10`, reset `i = 0`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The match at `m=10` fails immediately, so the algorithm next tries `m = 11` and `i = 0`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Once again, the algorithm matches `"ABCDAB"`, but the next character, `'C'`, does not match the final character `'D'` of the word `W`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Reasoning as before, the algorithm sets `m = 15`, to start at the two-character string `"AB"` leading up to the current position, set `i = 2`, and continue matching from the current position.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This time the match is complete, and the first character of the match is `S[15]`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The above example contains all the elements of the algorithm.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] For the moment, we assume the existence of a "partial match" table `T`, described below, which indicates where we need to look for the start of a new match when a mismatch is found.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The entries of `T` are constructed so that if we have a match starting at `S[m]` that fails when comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match will start at index `m + i - T[i]` in `S` (that is, `T[i]` is the amount of "backtracking" we need to do after a mismatch).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The following is a sample pseudocode implementation of the KMP search algorithm.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Assuming the prior existence of the table `T`, the search portion of the Knuth–Morris–Pratt algorithm has complexity *O*(*n*), where *n* is the length of `S` and the *O* is big-O notation.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Except for the fixed overhead incurred in entering and exiting the function, all the computations are performed in the `**while**` loop.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To bound the number of iterations of this loop; observe that `T` is constructed so that if a match which had begun at `S[m]` fails while comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match must begin at `S[m + (i - T[i])]`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In particular, the next possible match must occur at a higher index than `m`, so that `T[i] < i`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This fact implies that the loop can execute at most 2*n* times, since at each iteration it executes one of the two branches in the loop.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The first branch invariably increases `i` and does not change `m`, so that the index `m + i` of the currently scrutinized character of `S` is increased.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The second branch adds `i - T[i]` to `m`, and as we have seen, this is always a positive number.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the location `m` of the beginning of the current potential match is increased.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At the same time, the second branch leaves `m + i` unchanged, for `m` gets `i - T[i]` added to it, and immediately after `T[i]` gets assigned as the new value of `i`, hence `new_m + new_i = old_m + old_i - T[old_i] + T[old_i] = old_m + old_i`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the loop executes at most 2*n* times, showing that the time complexity of the search algorithm is *O*(*n*).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here is another way to think about the runtime: Let us say we begin to match `W` and `S` at position `i` and `p`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `W` exists as a substring of `S` at p, then `W[0..m] = S[p..p+m]`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon success, that is, the word and the text matched at the positions (`W[i] = S[p+i]`), we increase `i` by 1.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon failure, that is, the word and the text do not match at the positions (`W[i] ≠ S[p+i]`), the text pointer is kept still, while the word pointer is rolled back a certain amount (`i = T[i]`, where `T` is the jump table), and we attempt to match `W[T[i]]` with `S[p+i]`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The maximum number of roll-back of `i` is bounded by `i`, that is to say, for any failure, we can only roll back as much as we have progressed up to the failure.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The goal of the table is to allow the algorithm not to match any character of `S` more than once.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In other words, we "pre-search" the pattern itself and compile a list of all possible fallback positions that bypass a maximum of hopeless characters while not sacrificing any potential matches in doing so.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence `T[i]` is exactly the length of the longest possible *proper* initial segment of `W` which is also a segment of the substring ending at `W[i - 1]`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We use the convention that the empty string has length 0.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since a mismatch at the very start of the pattern is a special case (there is no possibility of backtracking), we set `T[0] = -1`, as discussed below.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We consider the example of `W = "ABCDABD"` first.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We will see that it follows much the same pattern as the main search, and is efficient for similar reasons.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To find `T[1]`, we must discover a proper suffix of `"A"` which is also a prefix of pattern `W`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But there are no proper suffixes of `"A"`, so we set `T[1] = 0`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However "B" is not a prefix of the pattern `W`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Continuing to `T[3]`, we first check the proper suffix of length 1, and as in the previous case it fails.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence at each stage, the shortcut rule is that one needs to consider checking suffixes of a given size m+1 only if a valid suffix of size m was found at the previous stage (i.e.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `T[x] = m`) and should not bother to check m+2, m+3, etc.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, we need not even concern ourselves with substrings having length 2, and as in the previous case the sole one with length 1 fails, so `T[3] = 0`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We pass to the subsequent `W[4]`, `'A'`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The same logic shows that the longest substring we need to consider has length 1, and as in the previous case it fails since "D" is not a prefix of `W`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But instead of setting `T[4] = 0`, we can do better by noting that `W[4] = W[0]`, and also that a look-up of `T[4]` implies the corresponding `S` character, `S[m+4]`, was a mismatch and therefore `S[m+4] ≠ 'A'`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus there is no point in restarting the search at `S[m+4]`; we should begin at 1 position ahead.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This means that we may shift pattern `W` by match length plus one character, so `T[4] = -1`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Considering now the next character, `W[5]`, which is `'B'`: though by inspection the longest substring would appear to be `'A'`, we still set `T[5] = 0`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The reasoning is similar to why `T[4] = -1`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `W[5]` itself extends the prefix match begun with `W[4]`, and we can assume that the corresponding character in `S`, `S[m+5] ≠ 'B'`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Finally, we see that the next character in the ongoing segment starting at `W[4] = 'A'` would be `'B'`, and indeed this is also `W[5]`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Furthermore, the same argument as above shows that we need not look before `W[4]` to find a segment for `W[6]`, so that this is it, and we take `T[6] = 2`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The example above illustrates the general technique for assembling the table with a minimum of fuss.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The principle is that of the overall search: most of the work was already done in getting to the current position, so very little needs to be done in leaving it.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The only minor complication is that the logic which is correct late in the string erroneously gives non-proper substrings at the beginning.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This necessitates some initialization code.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The time (and space) complexity of the table algorithm is $O(k)$ , where k is the length of `W`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Combined, the outer and inner loops take at most $2k-2$ iterations.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This corresponds to $O(k)$ time complexity using the Big O notation.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since the two portions of the algorithm have, respectively, complexities of `O(k)` and `O(n)`, the complexity of the overall algorithm is `O(n + k)`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] These complexities are independent of how many repetitive patterns are in `W` or `S`.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] It is known that the delay, that is the number of times a symbol of the text is compared to symbols of the pattern, is less than $\lfloor \log _{\Phi }(k+1)\rfloor$ , where Φ is the golden ration $(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2$ .
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In 1993, an algorithm was given that has a delay bounded by $\min(1+\lfloor \log _{2}k\rfloor ,|\Sigma |)$ where Σ is the size of the alphabet (of the pattern).
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A real-time version of KMP can be implemented using a separate failure function table for each character in the alphabet.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a mismatch occurs on character x in the text, the failure function table for character x is consulted for the index i in the pattern at which the mismatch took place.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This will return the length of the longest substring ending at i matching a prefix of the pattern, with the added condition that the character after the prefix is x .
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] With this restriction, character x in the text need not be checked again in the next phase, and so only a constant number of operations are executed between the processing of each index of the text.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This satisfies the real-time computing restriction.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Booth's algorithm uses a modified version of the KMP preprocessing function to find the lexicographically minimal string rotation.
[src:z-function-prefix/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The failure function is progressively calculated as the string is rotated.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] In computer science, **pattern matching** is the act of checking a given sequence of tokens for the presence of the constituents of some pattern.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] In contrast to pattern recognition, the match usually must be exact: "either it will or will not be a match." The patterns generally have the form of either sequences or tree structures.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Uses of pattern matching include outputting the locations (if any) of a pattern within a token sequence, to output some component of the matched pattern, and to substitute the matching pattern with some other token sequence (i.e., search and replace).
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Sequence patterns (e.g., a text string) are often described using regular expressions and matched using techniques such as backtracking.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Tree patterns are used in some programming languages as a general tool to process data based on its structure, e.g.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] C#, F#, Haskell, Java, ML, Python, Racket, Ruby, Rust, Scala, Swift and the symbolic mathematics language Mathematica have special syntax for expressing tree patterns and a language construct for conditional execution and value retrieval based on it.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Often it is possible to give alternative patterns that are tried one by one, which yields a powerful conditional programming construct.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Pattern matching sometimes includes support for guards.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Early programming languages with pattern matching constructs include COMIT (1957), SNOBOL (1962), which introduced pattern matching as a core, first-class language capability for string and text manipulation.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] This paradigm evolved into structured, tree-based data evaluation with Refal (1968), which used pattern matching to manipulate symbolic expressions.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The concept was soon adapted into logic programming with Prolog (1972), where pattern matching took the form of structural unification to resolve logical queries.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Functional programming languages rapidly adopted and formalized the feature across the late 1970s and early 1980s, beginning with the St Andrews Static Language (SASL) (1976), NPL (1977), and the Kent Recursive Calculator (KRC) (1981).
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The pattern matching feature of function arguments in the language ML (1973) and its dialect Standard ML (1983) heavily formalized compile-time exhaustiveness checking.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] This approach has been carried over to some other functional programming languages that were influenced by them, such as Haskell (1990), Scala (2004), and F# (2005).
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The pattern matching construct with the `match` keyword that was introduced in the ML dialect Caml (1985) was followed by languages such as OCaml (1996), F# (2005), F* (2011), and Rust (2015).
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Over time, multi-paradigm languages begin implementing algebraic data types and pattern matching natively, culminating in modern implementations like Python's `match-case` syntax (2021) and Java's pattern matching enhancements (2023).
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Many text editors support pattern matching of various kinds to facilitate advanced search-and-replace capabilities.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The QED editor, designed by Ken Thompson, was a pioneer in supporting regular expression searching.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Thompson's implementation of regular expression parsing in QED laid the groundwork for the text search utilities in ed, sed, and grep.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Furthermore, some versions of the TECO editor supported advanced matching features, including the logical OR operator in searches.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Computer algebra systems (CAS) generally support pattern matching on algebraic expressions to achieve symbolic simplification and integration.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Early systems like Macsyma (1968) used semantic pattern matching to recognize algebraic equivalence; for example, its internal engine could successfully match both `3x2 + 4` and `(x + 1)(x + 6)` as occurrences of a "quadratic in x" pattern template.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Modern computer algebra systems, including Mathematica and Maple, rely heavily on pattern-matching rules to transform user expressions, find analytical solutions to differential equations, and build user-defined simplification frameworks.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Pattern matching involves specialized terminology.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Pattern languages can be rich; see below for terminology denoting specific kinds of pattern.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The value to be examined and matched against a pattern.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Replacement of a portion of a scrutinee data structure with some computed value.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The computation may depend on the replaced portion of the scrutinee as well as on other bindings extracted from the scrutinee.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] While some concepts are relatively common to many pattern languages, other pattern languages include unique or unusual extensions.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] that portion when the continuation executes.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] , the wildcard pattern accepts all values without examining them further, ignoring their structure.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] is an expression that must succeed (or yield Boolean true) as a final step before considering a pattern to have successfully matched.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] ), guards are written using a restricted subset of the full language; in others (e.g.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The predicate is applied to the portion of the scrutinee corresponding to the position of the predicate in the pattern; if the predicate responds with Boolean false, the pattern is considered to have failed.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] to each element; the overall pattern thus succeeds only when the scrutinee is a list of even numbers.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] , where a user-defined function transforms the portion of the scrutinee corresponding to the position of the view pattern before continuing the match.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] View patterns generalize predicate patterns, allowing further matching on the result of the function rather than simply expecting a Boolean value.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Some pattern languages allow direct comparison of portions of the scrutinee with previously-computed (or constant) data structures.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] In Erlang, mention of any variable already in scope in a pattern causes it to act as a constraint in this way (instead of as a binding).
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Some languages allow macros in pattern context to allow abstraction over patterns.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The simplest pattern in pattern matching is an explicit value or a variable.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Now, whenever f is given 0 as argument the pattern matches and the function returns 1.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] With any other argument, the matching and thus the function fail.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Here, the first `n` is a single variable pattern, which will match absolutely any argument and bind it to name n to be used in the rest of the definition.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] In Haskell (unlike at least Hope), patterns are tried in order so the first definition still applies in the very specific case of the input being 0, while for any other argument the function returns `n * f (n-1)` with n being the argument.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The wildcard pattern (often written as `_`) is also simple: like a variable name, it matches any value, but does not bind the value to any name.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Algorithms for matching wildcards in simple string-matching situations have been developed in a number of recursive and non-recursive varieties.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] More complex patterns can be built from the primitive ones of the previous section, usually in the same way as values are built by combining other values.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The difference then is that with variable and wildcard parts, a pattern does not build into a single value, but matches a group of values that are the combination of the concrete elements and the elements that are allowed to vary within the structure of the pattern.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] A tree pattern describes a part of a tree by starting with a node and specifying some branches and nodes and leaving some unspecified with a variable or wildcard pattern.
