[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] By far the most common form of pattern matching involves strings of characters.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] In many programming languages, a particular syntax of strings is used to represent regular expressions, which are patterns describing string characters.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] However, it is possible to perform some string pattern matching within the same framework that has been discussed throughout this article.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, strings are represented as trees of root StringExpression and all the characters in order as children of the root.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Thus, to match "any amount of trailing characters", a new wildcard ___ is needed in contrast to _ that would match only a single character.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] In Haskell and functional programming languages in general, strings are represented as functional lists of characters.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] A functional list is defined as an empty list, or an element constructed on an existing list.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The structure for a list with some elements is thus `element:list`.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] When pattern matching, we assert that a certain piece of data is equal to a certain pattern.
