[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The main advantage of symbolic string manipulation is that it can be completely integrated with the rest of the programming language, rather than being a separate, special purpose subunit.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] The entire power of the language can be leveraged to build up the patterns themselves or analyze and transform the programs that contain them.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] SNOBOL (*StriNg Oriented and symBOlic Language*) is a computer programming language developed between 1962 and 1967 at AT&T Bell Laboratories by David J.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 stands apart from most programming languages by having patterns as a first-class data type (*i.e.* a data type whose values can be manipulated in all ways permitted to any other data type in the programming language) and by providing operators for pattern concatenation and alternation.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Strings generated during execution can be treated as programs and executed.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] SNOBOL was quite widely taught in larger US universities in the late 1960s and early 1970s and was widely used in the 1970s and 1980s as a text manipulation language in the humanities.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] Since SNOBOL's creation, newer languages such as AWK and Perl have made string manipulation by means of regular expressions fashionable.
[src:z-function-prefix/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 patterns, however, subsume Backus–Naur form (BNF) grammars, which are equivalent to context-free grammars and more powerful than regular expressions.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] In formal language theory and computer science, a **substring** is a contiguous sequence of characters within a string.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] For instance, "*the best of*" is a substring of "*It was the best of times*".
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] In contrast, "*Itwastimes*" is a subsequence of "*It was the best of times*", but not a substring.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A string u is a substring (or factor) of a string t if there exists two strings p and s such that $t=pus$ .
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] In particular, the empty string is a substring of every string.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] The first occurrence is obtained with $p={\texttt {b}}$ and $s={\texttt {na}}$ , while the second occurrence is obtained with $p={\texttt {ban}}$ and s being the empty string.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A substring of a string is a prefix of a suffix of the string, and equivalently a suffix of a prefix; for example, `nan` is a prefix of `nana`, which is in turn a suffix of `banana`.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] If u is a substring of t , it is also a subsequence, which is a more general concept.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] The occurrences of a given pattern in a given string can be found with a string searching algorithm.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] Finding the longest string which is equal to a substring of two or more strings is known as the longest common substring problem.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] In the mathematical literature, substrings are also called **subwords** (in America) or **factors** (in Europe).
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A string p is a prefix of a string t if there exists a string s such that $t=ps$ .
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A *proper prefix* of a string is not equal to the string itself; some sources in addition restrict a proper prefix to be non-empty.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A prefix can be seen as a special case of a substring.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] The square subset symbol is sometimes used to indicate a prefix, so that $p\sqsubseteq t$ denotes that p is a prefix of t .
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] This defines a binary relation on strings, called the prefix relation, which is a particular kind of prefix order.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A string s is a suffix of a string t if there exists a string p such that $t=ps$ .
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A *proper suffix* of a string is not equal to the string itself.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A more restricted interpretation is that it is also not empty.[1] A suffix can be seen as a special case of a substring.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A suffix tree for a string is a trie data structure that represents all of its suffixes.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] Suffix trees have large numbers of applications in string algorithms.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] The suffix array is a simplified version of this data structure that lists the start positions of the suffixes in alphabetically sorted order; it has many of the same applications.
