[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A **superstring** of a finite set P of strings is a single string that contains every string in P as a substring.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] For example, ${\texttt {bcclabccefab}}$ is a superstring of $P=\{{\texttt {abcc}},{\texttt {efab}},{\texttt {bccla}}\}$ , and ${\texttt {efabccla}}$ is a shorter one.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] Concatenating all members of P , in arbitrary order, always obtains a trivial superstring of P .
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] Finding superstrings whose length is as small as possible is a more interesting problem.
[src:z-function-prefix/prefix-computer-science] A string that contains every possible permutation of a specified character set is called a superpermutation.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] A **string-searching algorithm**, sometimes called **string-matching algorithm**, is an algorithm that searches a body of text for portions that match by pattern.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] In practice, the method of feasible string-search algorithm may be affected by the string encoding.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] In particular, if a variable-width encoding is in use, then it may be slower to find the *N*th character, perhaps requiring time proportional to *N*.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] This may significantly slow some search algorithms.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] One of many possible solutions is to search for the sequence of code units instead, but doing so may produce false matches unless the encoding is specifically designed to avoid it.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] The most basic case of string searching involves one (often very long) string, sometimes called the *haystack*, and one (often very short) string, sometimes called the *needle*.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] The goal is to find one or more occurrences of the needle within the haystack.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] One might request the first occurrence of "to", which is the fourth word; or all occurrences, of which there are 3; or the last, which is the fifth word from the end.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Very commonly, however, various constraints are added.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might want to match the "needle" only where it consists of one (or more) complete words—perhaps defined as *not* having other letters immediately adjacent on either side.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] In that case a search for "hew" or "low" should fail for the example sentence above, even though those literal strings do occur.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Another common example involves "normalization".
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Finally, for strings that represent natural language, aspects of the language itself become involved.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might wish to find all occurrences of a "word" despite it having alternate spellings, prefixes or suffixes, etc.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Another more complex type of search is regular expression searching, where the user constructs a pattern of characters or other symbols, and any match to the pattern should fulfill the search.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] where the "?" conventionally makes the preceding character ("u") optional.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] This article mainly discusses algorithms for the simpler kinds of string searching.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] A similar problem introduced in the field of bioinformatics and genomics is the maximal exact matching (MEM).
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Given two strings, MEMs are common substrings that cannot be extended left or right without causing a mismatch.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] A simple and inefficient way to see where one string occurs inside another is to check at each index, one by one.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] First, we see if there is a copy of the needle starting at the first character of the haystack; if not, we look to see if there's a copy of the needle starting at the second character of the haystack, and so forth.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] In this approach, backtracking is avoided by constructing a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that recognizes a stored search string.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] These are expensive to construct—they are usually created using the powerset construction—but are very quick to use.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] For example, the DFA shown to the right recognizes the word "MOMMY".
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] This approach is frequently generalized in practice to search for arbitrary regular expressions.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Knuth–Morris–Pratt computes a DFA that recognizes inputs with the string to search for as a suffix, Boyer–Moore starts searching from the end of the needle, so it can usually jump ahead a whole needle-length at each step.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Baeza–Yates keeps track of whether the previous *j* characters were a prefix of the search string, and is therefore adaptable to fuzzy string searching.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] The bitap algorithm is an application of Baeza–Yates' approach.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Faster search algorithms preprocess the text.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] After building a substring index, for example a suffix tree or suffix array, the occurrences of a pattern can be found quickly.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] As an example, a suffix tree can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, and all z occurrences of a pattern can be found in $O(m)$ time under the assumption that the alphabet has a constant size and all inner nodes in the suffix tree know what leaves are underneath them.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] The latter can be accomplished by running a DFS algorithm from the root of the suffix tree.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] Some search methods, for instance trigram search, are intended to find a "closeness" score between the search string and the text rather than a "match/non-match".
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] These are sometimes called "fuzzy" searches.
[src:z-function-prefix/string-searching-algorithm] The various algorithms can be classified by the number of patterns each uses.
