[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] In mathematics, the **Z function** is a function used for studying the Riemann zeta function along the critical line where the argument is one-half.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] It is also called the Riemann–Siegel Z function, the Riemann–Siegel zeta function, the Hardy function, the Hardy Z function and the Hardy zeta function.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] It follows from the functional equation of the Riemann zeta function that the Z function is real for real values of *t*.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] It is an even function, and real analytic for real values.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] It follows from the fact that the Riemann–Siegel theta function and the Riemann zeta function are both holomorphic in the critical strip, where the imaginary part of *t* is between −1/2 and 1/2, that the Z function is holomorphic in the critical strip also.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] Moreover, the real zeros of *Z*(*t*) are precisely the zeros of the zeta function along the critical line, and complex zeros in the Z function critical strip correspond to zeros off the critical line of the Riemann zeta function in its critical strip.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] Calculation of the value of *Z*(*t*) for real *t*, and hence of the zeta function along the critical line, is greatly expedited by the Riemann–Siegel formula.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] where the ellipsis indicates we may continue on to higher and increasingly complex terms.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] Other efficient series for Z(t) are known, in particular several using the incomplete gamma function.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] Hence, the number of zeros in an interval of a given size slowly increases.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] If the Riemann hypothesis is true, all of the zeros in the critical strip are real zeros, and the constant *c* is one.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] It is also postulated that all of these zeros are simple zeros.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] Because of the zeros of the Z function, it exhibits oscillatory behavior.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] It also slowly grows both on average and in peak value.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] where the notation means that $Z(t)$ divided by the function within the Ω does not tend to zero with increasing *t*.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] The average growth of the Z function has also been much studied.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] which tell us that the RMS size of *Z*(*t*) grows as ${\sqrt {\log t}}$ .
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] If we increase the exponent, we get an average value which depends more on the peak values of *Z*.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] Higher even powers have been much studied, but less is known about the corresponding average value.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] Here the little "o" notation means that the left hand side divided by the right hand side *does* converge to zero; in other words little o is the negation of Ω.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] This conjecture is called the Lindelöf hypothesis, and is weaker than the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] in either form it tells us the rate of growth of the peak values cannot be too high.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] The best known bound on this rate of growth is not strong, telling us that any $\epsilon >{\frac {89}{570}}\approx 0.156$ is suitable.
[src:z-function-prefix/z-function] It would be astonishing to find that the Z function grew anywhere close to as fast as this.
